    <!-- SECTION 1: PROJECT DESCRIPTION -->
    <h1>Project Description</h1>
    <p>
        <strong>EcoSense</strong> is an AI-powered waste management and environmental sustainability platform designed to help 
        individuals efficiently identify household waste items, discover step-by-step sorting instructions, locate nearby dropoff 
        facilities via maps, and monitor recycling progress through a centralized and user-friendly dashboard. The application 
        combines modern web technologies with Generative AI to simplify recycling procedures and improve public waste awareness.
    </p>
    <p>
        The system enables users to scan waste items, maintain historical logging records, locate local recycling centers, 
        generate AI-powered disposal protocol sheets, and create printable reports. By integrating intelligent automation and 
        cloud-based databases, EcoSense provides an efficient solution for organizing city-wide recycling information in one place.
    </p>
    <p>
        The application is developed using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript for the frontend, Python Flask for backend processing, 
        and Google Firebase Firestore (with local database fallback) as the cloud database. It integrates Groq's LLaMA 3.3-70B 
        Versatile model for AI-generated waste classification summaries, Leaflet.js maps for displaying nearby waste collection 
        centers, and Chart.js for visualization analytics. The frontend is deployed using GitHub Pages, while the backend is 
        deployed as a Render Web Service.
    </p>
    <p>
        EcoSense offers a responsive, secure, and easy-to-use interface that helps users organize waste disposal activities, 
        receive timely cleaning instructions, monitor scanning habits, generate AI-assisted disposal reports, and maintain 
        digital sustainability logs. The project demonstrates the practical application of Artificial Intelligence, cloud databases, 
        automation, and full-stack web development in solving real-world environmental management problems.
    </p>

    <h2>Key Features</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>AI-Powered Waste Classification & Guide Generation:</strong> Instantly categorizes items into 8 categories (Plastic, Paper, Glass, Organic, Metal, Hazardous, E-waste, Medical waste) with hazard level alerts.</li>
        <li><strong>Dynamic Disposal & Preparation Protocols:</strong> Lists custom actions (e.g. wash, caps removal) and eco suggestions (e.g. switch to rechargeable batteries) per scanned item.</li>
        <li><strong>Centralized Scan History Log Management:</strong> Saves previous scans automatically in the user's database, supporting single deletions or full stack resets.</li>
        <li><strong>Interactive Collection Center Map Locator:</strong> Uses Leaflet.js and OpenStreetMap coordinates to locate local waste hubs.</li>
        <li><strong>Color-Coded Marker Indicators:</strong> Renders custom map pins colored dynamically based on center categories (Red: Hazardous/E-waste, Green: General Recycle, Blue: Organic).</li>
        <li><strong>Dashboard Visualizations:</strong> Integrates Chart.js Doughnut charts, Bar charts, and Line graphs to represent recycling rates and scan volumes.</li>
        <li><strong>Printable Health Reports:</strong> Packs scanned logs, analytics, and AI guides into structured printable sheets.</li>
        <li><strong>Robust Heuristics Fallback Engine:</strong> Operates offline using a local JSON database when cloud credentials are not active.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="page-break"></div>

    <!-- SECTION 2: SCENARIOS -->
    <h1>Scenarios</h1>
    
    <h2>Scenario 1: Smart Waste Classification Scanner</h2>
    <p>
        A resident picks up an old battery at home and does not know how to dispose of it safely. They open EcoSense, 
        type "battery" into the waste scanner, and instantly receive a complete guide: the item is classified as 
        Hazardous Waste, the AI provides a hazard warning about toxic heavy metals, disposal instructions direct the user 
        to a certified battery collection point, and eco suggestions recommend switching to rechargeable batteries.
    </p>

    <h2>Scenario 2: Recyclable Sorting & Logging</h2>
    <p>
        A user wants to dispose of a plastic bottle responsibly. They enter "plastic bottle" into the scanner. The Groq AI 
        classifies it as Plastic Waste, confirms it is recyclable, provides four step-by-step recycling instructions including 
        rinsing and cap removal, and suggests switching to a reusable water bottle. The result is saved automatically to the 
        user's scan history.
    </p>

    <h2>Scenario 3: Interactive Collection Center Locator</h2>
    <p>
        After scanning a waste item, the user navigates to the Map page to find the nearest collection center. The Leaflet.js 
        map renders all nearby centers with color-coded markers for recycling, e-waste, organic, and hazardous facilities. 
        The user selects a center and views its address, opening hours, accepted waste types, and contact number.
    </p>

    <h2>Scenario 4: Cumulative Sustainability Analytics</h2>
    <p>
        A user opens the Dashboard to review their waste scanning habits. Chart.js renders a doughnut chart of recyclable 
        versus non-recyclable items, a 7-day line chart of daily scan frequency, and a bar chart of waste categories. 
        Summary statistics display total items scanned, recyclable count, recycle rate percentage, and hazardous item count.
    </p>

    <div class="page-break"></div>

    <!-- SECTION 3: TECHNICAL ARCHITECTURE -->
    <h1>Technical Architecture</h1>
    
    <div style="border: 1px dashed #d1d5db; padding: 20px; text-align: center; color: #10b981; font-weight: bold; margin-bottom: 5pt;">
        [Insert Figure 4.1: Technical Architecture Diagram of EcoSense Here]
    </div>
    <div class="figure-caption">Figure 4.1: Technical Architecture of EcoSense - AI Smart Sustainable Waste Assistant</div>

    <p>
        EcoSense follows a modern three-tier architecture that integrates a responsive web-based frontend, a cloud-based 
        backend, Artificial Intelligence services, and external database systems. The architecture is designed to provide 
        secure, scalable, and efficient waste management while ensuring seamless communication between users and cloud services.
    </p>
    <p>
        The frontend is developed using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, providing an intuitive and responsive interface for 
        waste scanning, history tracking, map coordinates filtering, dashboard analytics, and AI-powered report generation. 
        Users interact with the application through this interface to perform all waste-related activities.
    </p>
    <p>
        The application communicates with a Python Flask REST API, which acts as the backend service. The backend processes 
        user requests, validates input strings, manages business logic, communicates with external APIs, and performs database 
        CRUD operations.
    </p>
    <p>
        Patient scans, item category histories, dropoff locations, and logs are securely stored in Google Firebase Firestore, "
        which functions as the cloud database. If firebase configurations are not set, a local JSON database handles data storage.
    </p>
    <p>
        EcoSense integrates the Groq API using the LLaMA 3.3-70B Versatile large language model to generate AI-powered 
        classification summaries, sorting steps, and eco-friendly recommendations. Prompt engineering techniques are used 
        to transform text query entries into structured JSON outputs.
    </p>
    <p>
        The system integrates Leaflet.js maps connected to OpenStreetMap to deliver interactive coordinates mapping without cost. 
        The frontend is deployed using GitHub Pages, while backend services are deployed through Render Web Services.
    </p>

    <h2>Architecture Components</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Frontend:</strong> HTML, CSS, JavaScript, Responsive User Interface, Leaflet.js Maps, Chart.js Analytics</li>
        <li><strong>Backend:</strong> Python Flask, REST API Processing, Heuristics Fallback Engine</li>
        <li><strong>Cloud Database:</strong> Google Firebase Firestore NoSQL Database</li>
        <li><strong>Artificial Intelligence:</strong> Groq API (LLaMA 3.3-70B Versatile Model)</li>
        <li><strong>Deployment:</strong> GitHub Pages (Frontend), Render Web Service Container (Backend)</li>
    </ul>

